definition.value: Any salt prepared using acetic acid as the acid component.
The eleven-membered core polysaccharide derivative from Yokenella regensburgei strain PCM 2477.
The eleven-membered core polysaccharide derivitive from Yokenella regensburgei strain PCM 2476.

A mycolic acid produced by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Its structure is that of tetracosanoic acid substituted at position 2 by a 1-hydroxy-18-[2-(17-methoxy-18-methylhexatriacontyl)cyclopropyl]octadecyl group.

A mycolic acid produced by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Its structure is that of tetracosanoic acid substituted at position 2 by a 1-hydroxy-18-[2-(18-methyl-17-oxohexatriacontyl)cyclopropyl]octadecyl group.

A mycolic acid produced by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Its structure is that of hexacosanoic acid substituted at position 2 by a 1-hydroxy-16-{2-[14-(2-octadecylcyclopropyl)tetradecyl]cyclopropyl}hexadecyl group.

A lipooligosaccharide consisting of a phenolic phthiocerol core linked to the trisaccharide 3,6-di-O-methyl-alpha-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->4)-2,3-di-O-methyl-alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1->2)-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-rhamnopyranose.
A lipid derived from phthiocerol, having a 4-hydroxyphenyl substituent at the 29-position.
Any fatty acid containing anywhere in its structure a ring of atoms.
Any EC 3.4.* (hydrolases acting on peptide bond) inhibitor that inhibits the activity of a serine endopeptidase (EC 3.4.21.*).
A lipid-based glycol consisting of (3S,4R)-3-methoxy-4-methylnonacosane having (9R)- and (11S)-hydroxy substituents; a characteristic constituent of the waxes of tubercule bacilli.
An amido disaccharide fragment which mimicks the terminus of the O-polysaccharide of Vibrio cholerae O:1, serotype Ogawa (PDB entry: 1F4Y).
A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which each nitrogen is substituted by a 4-chloro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl group.
The (R)-enantiomer of bendroflumethiazide.
The (S)-enantiomer of bendroflumethiazide.
A monochlorobenzene that is the 3-trifluoromethyl derivative of 4-chloroaniline.
An organochlorine pesticide consisting of 1,3-diphenylurea having chloro substituents at the 3-, 4- and 5'-positions and a 4-chloro-2-sulfophenoxy group at the 2'-position.
The sodium salt of sulcofuron.
Conjugate base of sulcofuron.
A tetrasaccharide comprising four mannosyl residues joined by alpha(1->2) linkages.
A tetrasaccharide comprising four D-mannose residues joined by beta(1->2) linkages.
The (R)-enantiomer of betaxolol.
An organic anion arising from deprotonation of a acyclic tetrapyrrole compound.
The (S)-enantiomer of betaxolol.
The hydrochloride salt of (R)-betaxolol.
The hydrochloride salt of (S)-betaxolol.

A trisaccharide derivative and oligosaccharide phosphate comprised of one alpha-D-glucopyranosyl and two L-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptopyranosyl residues.  The sequence is present in enterobacterial lipopolysaccharide from all E. coli, Salmonella and Shigella.
An N-hydroxylated alpha-amino-acid anion.
A glycosylxylose derivative that comprises the highly antigenic lipooligosaccharide, LOS-III, epitope of Mycobacterium gastri.
The (R)-enantiomer of bethanechol.
The (S)-enantiomer of bethanechol.
The (R)-enantiomer of bethanechol chloride.
The (S)-enantiomer of bethanechol chloride.

A straight-chain, monounsaturated, 16-carbon fatty acid with a trans-double bond at position C-9; the trans-isomer of palmitoleic acid and predominant trans-16:1 isomer in cheeses from goat and ewe milk. Major dietary sources are partly hydrogenated vegetable oils.
An amino oligosaccharide that is a trisaccharide having one or more substituted or unsubstituted amino groups in place of hydroxy groups at unspecified positions.
An amido pentasaccharide fragment which mimicks the terminus of the O-polysaccharide of Vibrio cholerae O:1, serotype Ogawa.
A pentasaccharide derivative having one or more substituted or unsubstituted amino groups in place of hydroxy groups at unspecified positions.

The (pharmacologically active) (S)-(+)-enantiomer of brompheniramine. A histamine H1 receptor antagonist, it is used (commonly as its maleate salt) for the symptomatic relief of allergic conditions, including rhinitis and conjunctivitis.
A  long-chain fatty acid that is a derivative of myristic acid having a hydroxy substituent at C-2.
The gamma-D-glutamyl derivative of meso-diaminopimelic acid. Minimal ligand of NOD1.
An amido disaccharide comprising 4,6-dideoxy-4-(2-methoxypropanamido)-3-C-methyl-2-O-methyl-L-mannopyranose linked through the anomeric carbon to the 3-hydroxy group of L-fucose.

The maleic acid salt of the (pharmacologically active) (S)-(+)-enantiomer of brompheniramine.  A histamine H1 receptor antagonist, it is used for the symptomatic relief of allergic conditions, including rhinitis and conjunctivitis.
The methyl glycoside of L-xylopyranose.
The pyranose form of L-xylose.
D-glucosamine deoxygenated at C-6.
D-Quinovosamine acetylated on the amino nitrogen.
A disaccharide formed by an alpha1->3 glycosidic linkage between N-acetyl-L-galactosaminuronic acid and N-acetylquinovosamine.
A tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of alpha-L-rhamnose, alpha-D-galactose, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine and alpha-L-rhamnose residues in a linear (1->2, (1->3), (1->3) sequence.
A disaccharide consisting of alpha-L-rhamnose and alpha-D-galactose linked via a 1->2 glycosidic bond.
